                        "content": "The nurse is performing an assessment on a client with suspected irritable bowel syndrome (IBS). Which laboratory test would the nurse anticipate being ordered to confirm this diagnosis?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nIrritable bowel syndrome (IBS) is a gastrointestinal (GI) disorder that causes recurrent diarrhea (IBS-D), constipation (IBS-C), a combination of alternating diarrhea and constipation (IBS-A), or a mix of both diarrhea and constipation (IBS-M) with associated bloating and abdominal pain. There may be exacerbating factors, such as diet, stress, or anxiety. During an acute exacerbation, left lower quadrant pain may be present. Diagnostic evaluation of IBS can include routine laboratory tests, including a complete blood cell (CBC) count, serum albumin, erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), and stools for occult blood, which with IBS will all be normal. A hydrogen breath test is used to confirm IBS, as small-intestinal bacterial overgrowth or nutrient malabsorption that occurs with IBS will produce an excess amount of hydrogen. The excess hydrogen is exhaled via the lungs. Eliminate option 1 because this test is used in the diagnosis of Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori) infection. Eliminate option 2 because this test is used to diagnose cystic fibrosis. Lastly, eliminate option 4 because although this may be drawn in a client with suspected IBS, it is not specific to the diagnosis of this condition. Therefore, option 3 is correct.",
                        "id": "cd36caffe43b4da7a0a88ac825090009",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
                            {
                                "isRight": "1",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "6de220272e794bbf974e91163a1f3efb",
                                "content": "“I cannot have anything to eat or drink for at least 12 hours before the test.”"
